<TITLE> EU pledges to solve Bulgarian "evro" issue soon </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 LUXEMBOURG, Oct 15 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - The European Union pledged on Monday to solve quickly a dispute over the spelling of its common currency in Bulgarian, clearing the way for the signing of an agreement on closer ties with Montenegro, diplomats said. Sofia had threatened to delay the signature in its battle for the right to use the Bulgarian name "evro" for the euro in its Cyrillic alphabet, despite resistance from the European Central Bank. At a dawn meeting in Luxembourg, EU ambassadors approved a declaration recognising the existence of a "linguistic-technical problem" and vowing to solve it as soon as possible, in line with a 1995 summit decision on the currency's name. "The declaration was approved without discussion and without reservations," a Bulgarian spokeswoman said. Diplomats said the text was sufficient for Sofia to allow the signing of a Stabilisation and Association Agreement with Montenegro, the most recent independent state to emerge from the former Yugoslavia after it broke with Serbia last year. But Prime Minister Sergei Stanishev would make clear at a summit later this week that Bulgaria will not sign an EU reform treaty in December unless it obtains satisfaction on the "evro" by then, they said
